{{Citation needed|date=March 2013|sortkey=道国166たけのうちかいとう}}
{{right| 
[[File:Takenouchi-Touge01.JPG|thumb|none|256px|{{ill|Takenouchi Pass|ja|竹内峠}} (at the Osaka-Nara prefectural border). The left side is part of {{ill|National Route 166|ja|国道166号}}, while the right side shows the old highway.]]
}}
'''Takenouchi Highway''' (竹内街道) is the oldest ancient government road in Japan, stretching from {{ill|Sakai|ja|堺市}} in {{ill|Osaka Prefecture|ja|大阪府}} to the area near {{ill|Nagao Shrine|ja|長尾神社}} in {{ill|Katsuragi|ja|葛城市}}, {{ill|Nara Prefecture|ja|奈良県}}. Historically, it was known as '''Tajihi Road''' (丹比道).<ref>{{Cite book|lang=ja|title=Osaka no Kaidō (大阪の街道)|year=1989|publisher=Shōraisha|page=66}}</ref>

From the {{ill|Shiratori Intersection|ja|白鳥交差点}} in {{ill|Habikino|ja|羽曳野市}} to the vicinity of the Takenouchi settlement in Katsuragi, much of the route was designated as {{ill|National Route 166|ja|国道166号}} in 1974. In 2017, it became the first {{ill|Japan Heritage|ja|日本遺産}} site in Osaka.<ref>{{Cite web|lang=ja|title=Japan Heritage Recognition! Japan's Oldest National Route "Takenouchi Highway and Yokooji"|url=http://www.saikonokandou.com/2017/04/1470/|website=Saikonokandou.com|accessdate=2019-04-04}}</ref> Additionally, in {{ill|Taishi|ja|太子町 (大阪府)}}, major events such as the "Taishi Sacred Lantern Gathering" in spring and the "Takenouchi Highway Lantern Festival" in autumn are held annually.<ref>{{Cite web|lang=ja|url=http://www.town.taishi.osaka.jp/event_info/nenkangyouji1/1534900110524.html|title=FY2018 Annual Events|website=Taishi Town Official Website|publisher={{ill|Taishi|ja|太子町 (大阪府)}}|accessdate=2019-04-07}}</ref>

== Overview ==

The Takenouchi Highway is an ancient arterial road that traverses the southern foothills of {{ill|Mount Nijō|ja|二上山}}, connecting {{ill|Yamato Province|ja|大和国}} with {{ill|Kawachi Province|ja|河内国}}. It is regarded as Japan's oldest {{ill|ancient highway|ja|古代官道}}. Extending approximately 26 kilometers from the Daishōji area of Sakai to Nagao Shrine in Katsuragi (23 kilometers within Osaka Prefecture), it retains remnants of its original path.<ref>{{Cite book|lang=ja|author=Rom International (ed.)|date=2005|title=Road Map: Amazing Knowledge Encyclopedia (道路地図 びっくり!博学知識)|publisher=Kawade Shobō Shinsha|series=Kawade Yume Bunko|pages=52–53|isbn=4-309-49566-4}}</ref> Though the bustling cityscapes of Naniwa and Asuka have obscured its original width (once up to 30 meters during the {{ill|Asuka period|ja|飛鳥時代}}), the highway's historical significance as a transportation and cultural transmission route remains evident through its proximity to numerous ancient burial mounds, such as the {{ill|Emperor Ōjin's Mausoleum|ja|応神天皇陵}} and {{ill|Emperor Nintoku's Mausoleum|ja|仁徳天皇陵}}.<ref>{{Cite book|lang=ja|author=Kenji Asai|date=2001|title=Dictionary of Roads and Paths (道と路がわかる辞典)|publisher=Nihon Jitsugyō Shuppansha|isbn=4-534-03315-X}}</ref>

The highway's name derives from the Takenouchi settlement near the {{ill|Takenouchi Pass|ja|竹内峠}}, located in Katsuragi.{{sfn|Kenji Asai|2001}}

== History ==

The Takenouchi Highway is mentioned in the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀}} under the reign of {{ill|Empress Suiko|ja|推古天皇}} in 613 CE. It describes the establishment of a "grand road" connecting Naniwa (modern {{ill|Osaka|ja|大阪市}}) to the capital in Asuka.<ref>{{Cite book|lang=ja|author=Kenji Asai|date=2001|title=道と路がわかる辞典|publisher=Nihon Jitsugyō Shuppansha}}</ref> One theory suggests that {{ill|Prince Shōtoku|ja|聖徳太子}} commissioned the highway to facilitate diplomatic exchanges with the mainland, especially for envoys such as {{ill|Ono no Imoko|ja|小野妹子}} during missions to the {{ill|Sui dynasty|ja|隋}}.<ref>{{Cite book|lang=ja|author=Rom International (ed.)|date=2005|title=道路地図 びっくり!博学知識|publisher=Kawade Shobō Shinsha}}</ref>

During the {{ill|Asuka period|ja|飛鳥時代}}, the highway served as a conduit for the cultural and technological advancements brought by envoys and monks from the mainland. It played a pivotal role in transmitting the advanced culture and Buddhism that became foundational to Japanese civilization.{{sfn|Kenji Asai|2001}}

In the {{ill|Middle Ages|ja|中世}}, it remained a vital route as part of the {{ill|Ise Road|ja|伊勢街道}}. By 1890, it had been designated a prefectural road, and in 1974, it became part of {{ill|National Route 166|ja|国道166号}}.{{sfn|Rom International (ed.)|2005|p=52}} Thus, the highway has been in continuous use from the Asuka period to the present.

== Major Landmarks ==
{{right|
[[File:Ooshoji~daidousuji201512.JPG|thumb|225px|none|Daishōji Intersection, Sakai City (2015)]]
[[File:20041209竹之内街道02.JPG|thumb|225px|none|Takenouchi Highway, Sakai City]]
}}
; {{ill|Sakai|ja|堺市}}
* Daishōji Intersection (starting point)
* Kōno Shrine
* {{ill|Gold Spring Shrine|ja|金岡神社}}

