The Takenouchi Highway is an ancient arterial road that traverses the southern foothills of {{ill|Mount Nijō|ja|二上山|1=Futakami Mountain|2=ja|3=二上山|lt=Mount Futakami (or Nijo)|comment=Kanji are ambiguous between the two pronounciations|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, connecting {{ill|Yamato Province|ja|Yamato Province|qq=draft|qq=draft}} with {{ill|Kawachi Province|ja|河内国|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. It is regarded as Japan's oldest {{ill|ancient highway|ja|古代官道|1=Kaidō|lt=Ancient Kaidō|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Extending approximately 26 kilometers from the Daishōji area of Sakai to Nagao Shrine in Katsuragi (23 kilometers within Osaka Prefecture), it retains remnants of its original path.<ref>{{Cite book|lang=ja|author=Rom International (ed.)|date=2005|title=Road Map: Amazing Knowledge Encyclopedia (道路location map びっくり!博学知識)|publisher=Kawade Shobō Shinsha|series=Kawade Yume Bunko|pages=52–53|isbn=4-309-49566-4}}</ref> Though the bustling cityscapes of Naniwa and Asuka have obscured its original width (once up to 30 meters during the {{ill|Asuka period|ja|飛鳥時代|qq=draft|qq=draft}}), the highway's historical significance as a transportation and cultural transmission route remains evident through its proximity to numerous ancient Kofuns, such as.<ref>{{Cite book|lang=ja|author=Kenji Asai|date=2001|title=Dictionary of Roads and Paths (道と路がわかる辞典)|publisher=Nihon Jitsugyō Shuppansha|isbn=4-534-03315-X}}</ref>

* '''{{ill|Kondayama Kofun|ja|誉田御廟山古墳|1=Konda Gobyoyama Kofun|lt=Emperor Ōjin's Mausoleum|ja|応神天皇陵|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'''
* '''{{ill|Daisen Kofun|fi|Daisenry%C5%8D-kofun|pt|Daisenry%C5%8D-Kofun|fr|Kofun Daisenry%C5%8D|es|Daisenry%C5%8D-Kofun|en|Daisen Kofun|ca|Kofun Daisenry%C5%8D|ko|%EB%8B%A4%EC%9D%B4%EC%84%BC%EB%A6%AD %EA%B3%A0%EB%B6%84|zh|%E5%A4%A7%E4%BB%99%E9%99%B5%E5%8F%A4%E5%A2%B3|ja|大仙陵古墳|1=Daisenryō Kofun|lt=Emperor Nintoku's Mausoleum|ja|仁徳天皇陵|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'''
* '''{{ill|Empress Suiko's Mausoleum|ja|山田高塚古墳|1=Yamada Takatsuka Kofun|lt=Empress Suiko's Mausoleum (Yamada Takatsuka Kofun)|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'''

The highway's name derives from the Takenouchi settlement near the {{ill|Takenouchi Pass|ja|竹内峠|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, located in Katsuragi.{{sfn|Kenji Asai|2001}}

== History ==

The Takenouchi Highway is mentioned in the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|qq=draft|qq=draft}} under the reign of {{ill|Empress Suiko|ja|推古天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in 613 CE. It describes the establishment of a "grand road" connecting Naniwa (modern {{ill|Osaka|ja|大阪市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}) to the capital in Asuka.<ref>{{Cite book|lang=ja|author=Kenji Asai|date=2001|title=道と路がわかる辞典|publisher=Nihon Jitsugyō Shuppansha}}</ref> One theory suggests that {{ill|Prince Shōtoku|ja|聖徳太子|qq=draft|qq=draft}} commissioned the highway to facilitate diplomatic exchanges with the mainland, especially for envoys such as {{ill|Ono no Imoko|ja|小野妹子|qq=draft|qq=draft}} during missions to the {{ill|Sui dynasty|ja|隋|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref>{{Cite book|lang=ja|author=Rom International (ed.)|date=2005|title=道路location map びっくり!博学知識|publisher=Kawade Shobō Shinsha}}</ref>

During the {{ill|Asuka period|ja|飛鳥時代|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the highway served as a conduit for the cultural and technological advancements brought by envoys and monks from the mainland. It played a pivotal role in transmitting the advanced culture and Buddhism that became foundational to Japanese civilization.{{sfn|Kenji Asai|2001}}

In the {{ill|Middle Ages|ja|中世|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, it remained a vital route as part of the {{ill|Ise Road|ja|伊勢街道|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. By 1890, it had been designated a prefectural road, and in 1974, it became part of {{ill|National Route 166|ja|国道166号|1=Japan National Route 166|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.{{sfn|Rom International (ed.)|2005|p=52}} Thus, the highway has been in continuous use from the Asuka period to the present.

