* '''{{ill|Empress Suiko's Mausoleum|ja|山田高塚古墳|1=Yamada Takatsuka Kofun|lt=Empress Suiko's Mausoleum (Yamada Takatsuka Kofun)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Empress Suiko's Mausoleum|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamada Takatsuka Kofun|qq=}}'''

The highway's name derives from the Takenouchi settlement near the {{ill|Takenouchi Pass|ja|竹内峠|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takenouchi Pass|qq=}}, located in Katsuragi.{{sfn|Kenji Asai|2001}}

== History ==

The Takenouchi Highway is mentioned in the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nihon Shoki|qq=}} under the reign of {{ill|Empress Suiko|ja|推古天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Empress Suiko|qq=}} in 613 CE. It describes the establishment of a "grand road" connecting Naniwa (modern {{ill|Osaka|ja|大阪市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Osaka|qq=}}) to the capital in Asuka.<ref>{{Cite book|lang=ja|author=Kenji Asai|date=2001|title=道と路がわかる辞典|publisher=Nihon Jitsugyō Shuppansha}}</ref> One theory suggests that {{ill|Prince Shōtoku|ja|聖徳太子|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Prince Shōtoku|qq=}} commissioned the highway to facilitate diplomatic exchanges with the mainland, especially for envoys such as {{ill|Ono no Imoko|ja|小野妹子|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ono no Imoko|qq=}} during missions to the {{ill|Sui dynasty|ja|隋|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sui dynasty|qq=}}.<ref>{{Cite book|lang=ja|author=Rom International (ed.)|date=2005|title=道路location map びっくり!博学知識|publisher=Kawade Shobō Shinsha}}</ref>

During the {{ill|Asuka period|ja|飛鳥時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Asuka period|qq=}}, the highway served as a conduit for the cultural and technological advancements brought by envoys and monks from the mainland. It played a pivotal role in transmitting the advanced culture and Buddhism that became foundational to Japanese civilization.{{sfn|Kenji Asai|2001}}

In the {{ill|Middle Ages|ja|中世|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Middle Ages|qq=}}, it remained a vital route as part of the {{ill|Ise Road|ja|伊勢街道|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ise Road|qq=}}. By 1890, it had been designated a prefectural road, and in 1974, it became part of {{ill|National Route 166|ja|国道166号|1=Japan National Route 166|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/National Route 166|13=User:Immanuelle/Japan National Route 166|qq=}}.{{sfn|Rom International (ed.)|2005|p=52}} Thus, the highway has been in continuous use from the Asuka period to the present.

