{{right| 
[[File:Takenouchi-Touge01.JPG|thumb|none|256px|{{ill|Takenouchi Pass|ja|竹内峠|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takenouchi Pass|qq=}} (at the Osaka-Nara prefectural border). The left side is part of {{ill|National Route 166|ja|国道166号|1=Japan National Route 166|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/National Route 166|13=User:Immanuelle/Japan National Route 166|qq=}}, while the right side shows the old highway.]]
}}
'''Takenouchi Highway''' (竹内街道) is the oldest ancient government road in Japan, stretching from {{ill|Sakai|ja|堺市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sakai|qq=}} in {{ill|Osaka Prefecture|ja|大阪府|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Osaka Prefecture|qq=}} to the area near {{ill|Nagao Shrine|ja|長尾神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nagao Shrine|qq=}} in {{ill|Katsuragi|ja|葛城市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Katsuragi|qq=}}, {{ill|Nara Prefecture|ja|奈良県|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nara Prefecture|qq=}}. Historically, it was known as '''Tajihi Road''' (丹比道).<ref>{{Cite book|lang=ja|title=Osaka no Kaidō (大阪の街道)|year=1989|publisher=Shōraisha|page=66}}</ref>

From the {{ill|Shiratori Intersection|ja|白鳥交差点|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shiratori Intersection|qq=}} in {{ill|Habikino|ja|羽曳野市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Habikino|qq=}} to the vicinity of the Takenouchi settlement in Katsuragi, much of the route was designated as {{ill|National Route 166|ja|国道166号|1=Japan National Route 166|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/National Route 166|13=User:Immanuelle/Japan National Route 166|qq=}} in 1974. In 2017, it became the first {{ill|Japan Heritage|ja|日本遺産|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Japan Heritage|qq=}} site in Osaka.<ref>{{Cite web|lang=ja|title=Japan Heritage Recognition! Japan's Oldest National Route "Takenouchi Highway and Yokooji"|url=http://www.saikonokandou.com/2017/04/1470/|website=Saikonokandou.com|accessdate=2019-04-04}}</ref> Additionally, in {{ill|Taishi|ja|太子町 (大阪府)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Taishi|qq=}}, major events such as the "Taishi Sacred Lantern Gathering" in spring and the "Takenouchi Highway Lantern Festival" in autumn are held annually.<ref>{{Cite web|lang=ja|url=http://www.town.taishi.osaka.jp/event_info/nenkangyouji1/1534900110524.html|title=FY2018 Annual Events|website=Taishi Town Official Website|publisher={{ill|Taishi|ja|太子町 (大阪府)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Taishi|qq=}}|accessdate=2019-04-07}}</ref>

== Overview ==

The Takenouchi Highway is an ancient arterial road that traverses the southern foothills of {{ill|Mount Nijō|ja|二上山|1=Futakami Mountain|2=ja|3=二上山|lt=Mount Futakami (or Nijo)|comment=Kanji are ambiguous between the two pronounciations|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mount Nijō|13=User:Immanuelle/Futakami Mountain|qq=}}, connecting {{ill|Yamato Province|ja|大和国|qq=Yamato Province|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamato Province|qq=}} with {{ill|Kawachi Province|ja|河内国|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kawachi Province|qq=}}. It is regarded as Japan's oldest {{ill|ancient highway|ja|古代官道|1=Kaidō|lt=Ancient Kaidō|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/ancient highway|13=User:Immanuelle/Kaidō|qq=}}. Extending approximately 26 kilometers from the Daishōji area of Sakai to Nagao Shrine in Katsuragi (23 kilometers within Osaka Prefecture), it retains remnants of its original path.<ref>{{Cite book|lang=ja|author=Rom International (ed.)|date=2005|title=Road Map: Amazing Knowledge Encyclopedia (道路location map びっくり!博学知識)|publisher=Kawade Shobō Shinsha|series=Kawade Yume Bunko|pages=52–53|isbn=4-309-49566-4}}</ref> Though the bustling cityscapes of Naniwa and Asuka have obscured its original width (once up to 30 meters during the {{ill|Asuka period|ja|飛鳥時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Asuka period|qq=}}), the highway's historical significance as a transportation and cultural transmission route remains evident through its proximity to numerous ancient Kofuns, such as.<ref>{{Cite book|lang=ja|author=Kenji Asai|date=2001|title=Dictionary of Roads and Paths (道と路がわかる辞典)|publisher=Nihon Jitsugyō Shuppansha|isbn=4-534-03315-X}}</ref>

* '''{{ill|Kondayama Kofun|ja|誉田御廟山古墳|1=Konda Gobyoyama Kofun|lt=Emperor Ōjin's Mausoleum|ja|応神天皇陵|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kondayama Kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/Konda Gobyoyama Kofun|qq=}}'''
* '''{{ill|Daisen Kofun|fi|Daisenry%C5%8D-kofun|pt|Daisenry%C5%8D-Kofun|fr|Kofun Daisenry%C5%8D|es|Daisenry%C5%8D-Kofun|en|Daisen Kofun|ca|Kofun Daisenry%C5%8D|ko|%EB%8B%A4%EC%9D%B4%EC%84%BC%EB%A6%AD %EA%B3%A0%EB%B6%84|zh|%E5%A4%A7%E4%BB%99%E9%99%B5%E5%8F%A4%E5%A2%B3|ja|大仙陵古墳|1=Daisenryō Kofun|lt=Emperor Nintoku's Mausoleum|ja|仁徳天皇陵|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Daisen Kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/Daisenryō Kofun|qq=}}'''
* '''{{ill|Empress Suiko's Mausoleum|ja|山田高塚古墳|1=Yamada Takatsuka Kofun|lt=Empress Suiko's Mausoleum (Yamada Takatsuka Kofun)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Empress Suiko's Mausoleum|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamada Takatsuka Kofun|qq=}}'''

The highway's name derives from the Takenouchi settlement near the {{ill|Takenouchi Pass|ja|竹内峠|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takenouchi Pass|qq=}}, located in Katsuragi.{{sfn|Kenji Asai|2001}}

