<!--Takeuchi Highway--><!--Takeuchi Highway-->

{{Citation needed|date=March 2013|sortkey=道国166たけのうちかいとう}}
{{right| 
[[File:Takenouchi-Touge01.JPG|thumb|none|256px|{{ill|Takenouchi Pass|ja|竹内峠|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takenouchi Pass|qq=}} (at the Osaka-Nara prefectural border). The left side is part of [[:en:Japan National Route 166|Japan National Route 166]], while the right side shows the old highway.]]
}}
'''Takenouchi Highway''' (竹内街道) is the oldest ancient government road in Japan, stretching from [[:en:Sakai|Sakai]] in [[:en:Osaka Prefecture|Osaka Prefecture]] to the area near [[:en:Nagao Shrine|Nagao Shrine]] in [[:en:Katsuragi, Nara|Katsuragi]], [[:en:Nara Prefecture|Nara Prefecture]]. Historically, it was known as '''Tajihi Road''' (丹比道).<ref>{{Cite book|lang=ja|title=Osaka no Kaidō (大阪の街道)|year=1989|publisher=Shōraisha|page=66}}</ref>

From the {{ill|Shiratori Intersection|ja|白鳥交差点|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shiratori Intersection|qq=}} in [[:en:Habikino|Habikino]] to the vicinity of the Takenouchi settlement in Katsuragi, much of the route was designated as [[:en:Japan National Route 166|Japan National Route 166]] in 1974. In 2017, it became the first [[:en:Japan Heritage|Japan Heritage]] site in Osaka.<ref>{{Cite web|lang=ja|title=Japan Heritage Recognition! Japan's Oldest National Route "Takenouchi Highway and Yokooji"|url=http://www.saikonokandou.com/2017/04/1470/|website=Saikonokandou.com|accessdate=2019-04-04}}</ref> Additionally, in [[:en:Taishi, Osaka|Taishi]], major events such as the "Taishi Sacred Lantern Gathering" in spring and the "Takenouchi Highway Lantern Festival" in autumn are held annually.<ref>{{Cite web|lang=ja|url=http://www.town.taishi.osaka.jp/event_info/nenkangyouji1/1534900110524.html|title=FY2018 Annual Events|website=Taishi Town Official Website|publisher=[[:en:Taishi, Osaka|Taishi]]|accessdate=2019-04-07}}</ref>

== Overview ==

The Takenouchi Highway is an ancient arterial road that traverses the southern foothills of {{ill|Mount Nijō|ja|二上山|1=Futakami Mountain|2=ja|3=二上山|lt=Mount Futakami (or Nijo)|comment=Kanji are ambiguous between the two pronounciations|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mount Nijō|13=User:Immanuelle/Futakami Mountain|qq=}}, connecting [[:en:Yamato Province|Yamato Province]] with [[:en:Kawachi Province|Kawachi Province]]. It is regarded as Japan's oldest {{ill|ancient highway|ja|古代官道|1=Kaidō|lt=Ancient Kaidō|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/ancient highway|13=User:Immanuelle/Kaidō|qq=}}. Extending approximately 26 kilometers from the Daishōji area of Sakai to Nagao Shrine in Katsuragi (23 kilometers within Osaka Prefecture), it retains remnants of its original path.<ref>{{Cite book|lang=ja|author=Rom International (ed.)|date=2005|title=Road Map: Amazing Knowledge Encyclopedia (道路location map びっくり!博学知識)|publisher=Kawade Shobō Shinsha|series=Kawade Yume Bunko|pages=52–53|isbn=4-309-49566-4}}</ref> Though the bustling cityscapes of Naniwa and Asuka have obscured its original width (once up to 30 meters during the [[:en:Asuka period|Asuka period]]), the highway's historical significance as a transportation and cultural transmission route remains evident through its proximity to numerous ancient Kofuns, such as.<ref>{{Cite book|lang=ja|author=Kenji Asai|date=2001|title=Dictionary of Roads and Paths (道と路がわかる辞典)|publisher=Nihon Jitsugyō Shuppansha|isbn=4-534-03315-X}}</ref>

* '''{{ill|Kondayama Kofun|ja|誉田御廟山古墳|1=Konda Gobyoyama Kofun|lt=Emperor Ōjin's Mausoleum|ja|応神天皇陵|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kondayama Kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/Konda Gobyoyama Kofun|qq=}}'''
* '''{{ill|Daisen Kofun|fi|Daisenry%C5%8D-kofun|pt|Daisenry%C5%8D-Kofun|fr|Kofun Daisenry%C5%8D|es|Daisenry%C5%8D-Kofun|en|Daisen Kofun|ca|Kofun Daisenry%C5%8D|ko|%EB%8B%A4%EC%9D%B4%EC%84%BC%EB%A6%AD %EA%B3%A0%EB%B6%84|zh|%E5%A4%A7%E4%BB%99%E9%99%B5%E5%8F%A4%E5%A2%B3|ja|大仙陵古墳|1=Daisenryō Kofun|lt=Emperor Nintoku's Mausoleum|ja|仁徳天皇陵|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Daisen Kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/Daisenryō Kofun|qq=}}'''
* '''{{ill|Empress Suiko's Mausoleum|ja|山田高塚古墳|1=Yamada Takatsuka Kofun|lt=Empress Suiko's Mausoleum (Yamada Takatsuka Kofun)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Empress Suiko's Mausoleum|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamada Takatsuka Kofun|qq=}}'''

The highway's name derives from the Takenouchi settlement near the {{ill|Takenouchi Pass|ja|竹内峠|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takenouchi Pass|qq=}}, located in Katsuragi.{{sfn|Kenji Asai|2001}}

== History ==

The Takenouchi Highway is mentioned in the [[:en:Nihon Shoki|Nihon Shoki]] under the reign of [[:en:Empress Suiko|Empress Suiko]] in 613 CE. It describes the establishment of a "grand road" connecting Naniwa (modern [[:en:Osaka|Osaka]]) to the capital in Asuka.<ref>{{Cite book|lang=ja|author=Kenji Asai|date=2001|title=道と路がわかる辞典|publisher=Nihon Jitsugyō Shuppansha}}</ref> One theory suggests that [[:en:Prince Shōtoku|Prince Shōtoku]] commissioned the highway to facilitate diplomatic exchanges with the mainland, especially for envoys such as [[:en:Ono no Imoko|Ono no Imoko]] during missions to the [[:en:Sui dynasty|Sui dynasty]].<ref>{{Cite book|lang=ja|author=Rom International (ed.)|date=2005|title=道路location map びっくり!博学知識|publisher=Kawade Shobō Shinsha}}</ref>

During the [[:en:Asuka period|Asuka period]], the highway served as a conduit for the cultural and technological advancements brought by envoys and monks from the mainland. It played a pivotal role in transmitting the advanced culture and Buddhism that became foundational to Japanese civilization.{{sfn|Kenji Asai|2001}}

In the [[:en:Middle Ages|Middle Ages]], it remained a vital route as part of the {{ill|Ise Road|ja|伊勢街道|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ise Road|qq=}}. By 1890, it had been designated a prefectural road, and in 1974, it became part of [[:en:Japan National Route 166|Japan National Route 166]].{{sfn|Rom International (ed.)|2005|p=52}} Thus, the highway has been in continuous use from the Asuka period to the present.

